</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E401256FDA00FB8A7FE83F4C938586E0" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="7BEBAA641BB38285425C5D42B95C74F9" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6F2EE356AF46C5B10031F3DFC536C361" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">The species was collected in bloom in August and had inflorescences in different stages of development, which suggests that the flowering period may be much broader.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3721E9392AA4E0039A013CCB79CF1DFC" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="A6EA8BE054042D8709350C41D4EB54C2" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F196874A902F63BCA1411D8323CE20FC" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">The specific epithet refers to the provinces of El Oro and Loja, since this species was discovered at their border.</paragraph>
<caption id="9640E589BA1B5952DAE60089690026F3" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574521" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" start="Figure 5" startId="F5">
<paragraph id="F40B0D8FA7368631668636247D36109E" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="5A6380A25927819ED759840FA6C8D1DA" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Figure 5.</emphasis>
Landscape near to Cerro de Arcos, where 
<taxonomicName id="9325F6AE60DA65C42F6F819BBC611DEA" authorityName="Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez" authorityYear="2021" class="Aves" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepanthes oro-lojaensis" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis id="9BD4946327DF51AEE8FAAF9A1627AB21" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Lepanthes oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected, in El Oro Province 
<emphasis id="3C19F4142EB0A3E603BDE59C24B07EC7" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">A</emphasis>
natural vegetation remnants 
<emphasis id="EC5F79ACA00A971471D213B105F93201" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">B</emphasis>
areas where 
<taxonomicName id="90B02F729CC5FE7B691A5CD61BEE6FC0" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="92AF308C4ED0BCC3780D4972BDADC98A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Pinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been planted.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0E85AC4F3D15E921ECCF3246DF0607A4" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="preliminary conservation status">
<paragraph id="A75D8F1BD5BC47ACE4BA891ACCBAB7AE" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Preliminary conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="38B820D7B33E6F7D81C07960780AC796" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<taxonomicName id="BDB6164C2A3FB8350AD672F0716B9BB0" authorityName="Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez" authorityYear="2021" class="Aves" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepanthes oro-lojaensis" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis id="ECDDEC55A012895421A6A9EBBBA425B2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Lepanthes oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is known only from the type location, and only two mature individuals were observed. After its discovery in 2015, two additional visits were conducted to explore surrounding areas but it was not possible to find more plants. However, it was evident that the original habitat is under strong pressure due to cattle ranching, the collection of remaining shrubs as firewood and a rapid transformation and fragmentation of the surrounding landscape due to fires and exotic species plantations such as 
<taxonomicName id="36CE2169BE383FD431A6CB39C4026C2A" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus radiata" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="radiata">
<emphasis id="471B50D416D428B6A7FB649D3B5F87D2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Pinus radiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
D.Don (
<bibRefCitation id="D831E48F7490211AB6516908289E0FCA" author="Penafiel, M" editor="Fernandez-Fernadez, D" journalOrPublisher="GADPEO-INABIO, Quito" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="27 - 46" refId="B17" refString="Penafiel, M, Fernandez-Fernadez, D, Freire, E, Tobar, F, Munoz-Yanez, M, 2018. Introduccion. In: Fernandez-Fernadez, D, Garzon-Santomaro, C, Munoz-Yanez, M, Gonzales, D, Mena-Jaen, JL, Eds., ORQUIDEAS Y BROMELIAS DE LA PROVINCIA DE EL ORO: Una guia de identificacion para los principales generos y especies del paramo al manglar. GADPEO-INABIO, Quito: 27 - 46" title="Introduccion." volumeTitle="ORQUIDEAS Y BROMELIAS DE LA PROVINCIA DE EL ORO: Una guia de identificacion para los principales generos y especies del paramo al manglar." year="2018">Penafiel et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Therefore, its small population size, area of occupancy of four km2, as well as its habitat restriction and degradation of its unique location allow us to apply criteria B of the 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCD429DC39CCDB1DF60E9E607B7A859" author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="University of Goeteborg, Stockholm" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" publicationUrl="https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/10315" refId="B8" refString="IUCN, 2012. IUCN red list categories and criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge. https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/10315" title="IUCN red list categories and criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge." url="https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/10315" year="2012">IUCN (2012)</bibRefCitation>
Red List. The species is preliminarily assessed as Critically Endangered (CR) B2a+b(ii,iii,v) given that it is known from a single location where its area of occupancy, habitat quality, and number of mature individuals are probably declining.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3516A1381D078E20D5551552FB74C75C" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2202AC49AE279212A75CF0E45E8D4592" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="30641F5D97E6BC4EF15FF8890E861D03" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
Morphologically, the most similar species is 
<taxonomicName id="4AB41B532C6A11E4F60F838698D9ABB9" class="Aves" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepanthes jimburae" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jimburae">
<emphasis id="D5485C36CD65559D1489593779A1D1CF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Lepanthes jimburae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="84CBD8F65069E67B8B1CEA285A1C4E83" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Comparison with the most similar species to Lepanthes oro-lojaensis Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez A Lepanthes oro-lojaensis B Lepanthes jimburae C Lepanthes corkyae D Lepanthes schizix. Photographs by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574519" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3b</figureCitation>
) from the southeastern slopes of the Ecuadorian Andes. From that species, 
<taxonomicName id="A8F3D7ACB42DCB2C725A2810882E70C4" genus="L." lsidName="L. oro-lojaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis id="A5E1DB60B91493EBED0D4508A7EA9D6C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the smaller plants, the dorsal sepal attenuate into a shorter decurved cauda, the lateral sepals with minutely denticulate margins and petals with the upper lobe ovate, with rounded apex and lower lobe triangular-oblong. The new species is also similar to 
<taxonomicName id="C593C5CCF90B6FD4D9AA04F9EA294454" genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis id="1EE7C7E50B905AD6B4BC677BB1024825" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AA7F885302E07D221D593A7C9388A4C5" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Comparison with the most similar species to Lepanthes oro-lojaensis Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez A Lepanthes oro-lojaensis B Lepanthes jimburae C Lepanthes corkyae D Lepanthes schizix. Photographs by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574519" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3c</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="2C520362995AB09CB9DAC2998CC0CC43" genus="L." lsidName="L. schizix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="schizix">
<emphasis id="A22B99E90DB03C4A37247B8A528119EE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. schizix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5F6A4C00B143BA9035EE49EDF5229F9B" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Comparison with the most similar species to Lepanthes oro-lojaensis Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez A Lepanthes oro-lojaensis B Lepanthes jimburae C Lepanthes corkyae D Lepanthes schizix. Photographs by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574519" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3d</figureCitation>
), both occurring on the western slopes of the northern Ecuador and from which it differs in the red to reddish with yellow dorsal sepals, yellow lateral sepals suffused with red around the mid-vein (vs. orange to red brown sepals in 
<taxonomicName id="73B14E705160C96823BBE8279902BA31" genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis id="0AFC24CAB2D0BA019319120544388205" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and purple flower in 
<emphasis id="DBF575435A0623D5D6BE51A3D5068EDB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
L 
<taxonomicName id="01EC1DEED995D1D014424DE0C14198BE" class="Aves" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepanthes schizix" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schizix">Lepanthes schizix</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
), lateral sepals in 
<taxonomicName id="DD410053A7C9C7D5C893ED1382947C3A" genus="L." lsidName="L. oro-lojaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis id="F391B886C884CAA8FB55168BB8DD604A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are minutely denticulate in the margin, are no denticulate in 
<taxonomicName id="E1B0C759CB2E164A55DA351C1F11173E" genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis id="4BF07DD5C770ADA5EF69B2F406EDCEDB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and minutely ciliate in 
<taxonomicName id="0385AA41B4A18EA417087A2988E57553" genus="L." lsidName="L. schizix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="schizix">
<emphasis id="AC2988D463C1C743494B0B38F1BD8FEC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. schizix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In Both 
<taxonomicName id="EEC061F4BD2646EB98DB7173966B8606" genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis id="AC795372478226FA23DD13DC3A05F880" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A37FFE26716158AC52E5F6854B4898FB" genus="L." lsidName="L. schizix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="schizix">
<emphasis id="176428C53803CBF1285D788A16869116" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. schizix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the lip blade are glabrous (vs. microscopically pubescent 
<taxonomicName id="8F68F377220E00EDAD98997EB6834AFA" genus="L." lsidName="L. oro-lojaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis id="27EA58F3391AC0B2452FEC1710E7FA77" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and, lip blades are oblong in 
<taxonomicName id="A417E296397FA11BD5517651E5A36409" genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis id="24A6060ED55AF7DC91A6A184578DA388" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="EA829862D61220FFDA60D5076CC22677" genus="L." lsidName="L. oro-lojaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis id="D80109F70B4D69D4DECF6E020476D01E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and lunate in 
<taxonomicName id="1366C70F29AE31AF9E13130403AD8EF0" genus="L." lsidName="L. schizix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="schizix">
<emphasis id="655675445FADF378753913F2D91370D0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. schizix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
